Welcome to the first notebook in this Java track. The goal of this session is small but solid. Here is the map for what we will cover. You will learn what Java is, and why it still anchors enterprise systems in 2026. You will learn how the java virtual machine's compile and run pipeline works. You will install Java twenty one with Eclipse Temurin. You will see the three ways to run Java code, namely jshell, jbang, and Maven. You will learn about values, the distinction between primitive types and reference types, and how autoboxing bridges them. You will meet the keyword var and local variable type inference. You will learn the difference between expressions and statements, and where the modern switch blurs that line. You will see the operators, including the famous double equals versus dot equals gotcha. You will see the control flow constructs. The if statement. The while loop. The for loop, both classic and enhanced. The switch in both statement and expression forms. You will learn how methods are declared, how overloading works, and what the void marker means. You will work with strings and text blocks, and you will see why string immutability matters. And finally you will see Java's comment styles, including javadoc. Prior programming experience helps but it is not required. If you have written Python or Scala, you will see familiar shapes here, just dressed in slightly more verbose clothing. Java asks you to spell more out than Python does, and the trade you get for that verbosity is a type system you can read at a glance, and a runtime that has been hardened by twenty five years of production use.

Let us start with the simplest possible question. What is Java. Java is a statically typed, class based, object oriented language that compiles to bytecode and runs on the java virtual machine. That single sentence is dense, so let us unpack it.

Statically typed means every variable has a type that the compiler knows at compile time. If you try to add a string and an integer, the compiler stops you before the program ever runs. This is the opposite of Python, where the same mistake only blows up at runtime when the offending line actually executes.

Class based and object oriented means code lives inside classes. The class is the unit of encapsulation, of inheritance, and even of the file system layout. One public class per file, and the file name has to match the class name. Java pushes you toward classes hard, in a way that Scala and Python do not.

Compiles to bytecode and runs on the java virtual machine means the Java compiler does not produce machine code for your laptop's processor. It produces a portable instruction set called java virtual machine bytecode. Any java virtual machine on any operating system can then load that bytecode and execute it. This is the origin of Java's famous old slogan, write once, run anywhere.

Java was created by James Gosling and his team at Sun Microsystems in 1995. Four traits define modern Java in one breath. It is statically typed, so type mismatches are caught at compile time. It is class based and object oriented. It is memory managed, which means the java virtual machine's garbage collector reclaims unreachable objects for you. You never call free. And it is backwards compatible to a fault. Code written in 1998 still compiles and runs on Java 21 with very few exceptions. The Java ecosystem rewards stability above all else.

Now, why Java in 2026. There are three reasons people pick this language today. The first is enterprise ubiquity. Banks, telecoms, governments, and large e commerce platforms run on Java. The largest backends in the world are Java backends. The hiring market is enormous, and is unlikely to shrink for a long time.

The second reason is the Spring ecosystem. Spring, and especially Spring Boot, are the dominant backend framework on the java virtual machine. Most production microservices you will ever read are Spring services. Notebooks 08 through 12 in this track are entirely about Spring, so we are pointing toward that goal from the very first lesson.

The third reason is performance and tooling. The java virtual machine has a mature garbage collector. It has a just in time compiler that watches your program run and rewrites the hot paths into optimized machine code. And it has the best profiling and observability tools on any platform, with things like jstack, jmap, java flight recorder, and async profiler all built around it.

A short word on language versions. This track targets Java 21, the current long term support release. Java has evolved enormously since the late nineties, and a lot of older tutorials still teach the 1998 dialect. We will write modern Java throughout. Five features you will use constantly that did not exist in old Java. The keyword var, which lets you skip the type on a local variable and have the compiler infer it. Text blocks, which are triple quoted multi line string literals. Records, which give you one line immutable data classes. Pattern matching for switch, which lets switch act as an expression that destructures values. And virtual threads, which let you run millions of cheap threads on the same java virtual machine.

If you ever land on a Stack Overflow answer where someone defines a class just to hold three fields with getters and setters, that is old Java. The shape of the problem is the same. Modern Java solves it in one line with a record.

Let us spend a minute on what happens when you run a Java program. When you write a Java source file, the compiler is called javac. The compiler turns your source code into java virtual machine bytecode. The bytecode is portable. The java virtual machine then loads the bytecode, executes it, garbage collects unused memory, and uses its just in time compiler to optimize the hot paths in your program as it runs.

Two consequences are worth absorbing now. The first is that startup is not instant. The java virtual machine itself takes a moment to boot. For tiny one off scripts this feels slow. For long running services it disappears into the noise. The second consequence is that you inherit the java virtual machine's strengths. A mature garbage collector. A just in time compiler that actually gets faster the longer your program runs. And decades of mature profiling and observability tools.

Now let us install Java and actually run something. The recommended distribution is Eclipse Temurin, a free production grade build of OpenJDK maintained by the Adoptium project. On macOS you install it with brew install dash dash cask temurin. While you are at it, install jbang, which is a single file Java script runner, and Maven and Gradle, which are the two dominant multi file build tools. After installation, open a new terminal so the updated path takes effect. Then verify the install. Type java dash dash version, and you should see openjdk twenty one point something. Type javac dash dash version to confirm the compiler is on your path. Type jshell dash dash version to confirm the interactive shell, which ships with the java development kit. Type jbang dash dash version and m v n dash dash version to confirm the rest.

Now, Java gives you three on ramps for running code. Pick the one that matches the size of what you are doing.

The first on ramp is the interactive shell, called jshell. The jshell tool is for the question, what does this expression do. It is the cheapest possible feedback loop. You type an expression. Java evaluates it. Java echoes back the result. You think. You type the next expression. The jshell tool is where you build intuition.

The second on ramp is jbang. The jbang tool is for a single Java file you want to keep around. You write your code in a file called something dot java. You add a shebang line and a Java version comment at the top of the file, and you run the file directly with jbang. If your script needs a library, you add a special comment declaring the dependency, and jbang fetches it for you. This is the perfect tool for personal scripts and small experiments.

The third on ramp is Maven, or its cousin Gradle. Maven is for anything that has more than one file, or that you want to build, test, and deploy seriously. Maven is also what every Spring project uses. It manages dependencies, runs your tests, compiles incrementally as you save files, and packages your application into a jar archive you can deploy.

Let us see each of these in action. Open the interactive shell with the jshell command. You will get a prompt that says jshell greater than. From there, type system dot out dot print line, in quotes, hello java twenty one. The jshell tool prints back hello java twenty one. Now type var name equals, in quotes, ganesh. The jshell tool binds the name and echoes back that the variable is now a string. Now type, in quotes, hello comma space, plus name. That returns the string hello comma ganesh, and binds it to an auto generated variable name. When you are done, type slash exit to quit. The slash help command shows all jshell commands. They all start with a forward slash, which is how you talk to the shell itself rather than to the Java language.

Three details worth registering from that session. First, var let us declare a local variable without writing the type. The compiler inferred string from the right hand side. Second, a bare expression on its own gets evaluated and bound to a generated name like dollar three, so you can refer to it in the next prompt. Third, the slash prefixed commands are jshell commands, not Java statements. They are the meta language of the shell.

Next, jbang. For anything longer than two lines you put the code in a file. Create a file called hello dot java. At the top, write the shebang line that tells the system to run the file with jbang. On the next line, write a comment that says java twenty one, which pins the language version. Then write a public class called hello, with a public static void main method that takes a string array called args, and inside that method call system dot out dot print line with the string hello from jbang. To run the file, type jbang hello dot java. The output is hello from jbang.

Three new shapes appeared in that example. The shebang line at the top, combined with making the file executable, lets you run the file directly. The slash slash java twenty one comment is a jbang directive that pins the language version for this file. And the public static void main method is Java's entry point signature. Every standalone Java program starts in a method with this exact shape. Public means accessible from anywhere. Static means it belongs to the class itself rather than to an instance. Void means it returns nothing. And the string array parameter holds the command line arguments. Modern Java has a preview feature called implicit main that drops this boilerplate, but the classic form is still what you will read everywhere, so it is the form to learn first.

Now, Maven. For a real project, Maven gives you a directory layout, dependency management, and a test runner. You will meet Maven properly in notebook seven. For now, the one command scaffold is enough. Type m v n archetype generate, with a group identifier, an artifact identifier, the quickstart archetype identifier, and interactive mode false. That creates a directory with the standard Maven layout. There is a p o m dot x m l file at the root that holds your project configuration. The src slash main slash java subdirectory holds your production code. The src slash test slash java subdirectory holds your tests. To compile and run the generated app, type m v n compile exec colon java, with the main class system property pointing at the generated class.

Now we shift from setup to the language itself. Every value in Java has a type the compiler knows at compile time. Types come in two flavours. Primitive types are built into the language and store their value directly. The primitive types are int, long, double, float, boolean, char, byte, and short. Reference types are everything else. Every class is a reference type. A variable of a reference type holds a reference, essentially a pointer, to an object that lives on the heap. String, list of integer, arrays, and any class you define are all reference types.

The distinction matters because primitives live on the stack with their value embedded directly into the variable, while reference typed values are references that point to a heap allocated object. We will return to this in notebook seven when we talk about java virtual machine memory in detail.

Every primitive type has a boxed reference type partner. The int primitive boxes to Integer with a capital I. The long primitive boxes to Long with a capital L. The boolean primitive boxes to Boolean with a capital B, and so on. The compiler autoboxes between them when needed. If you write Integer x equals forty two, the compiler silently wraps the forty two in Integer dot value of forty two. Autoboxing is convenient but it allocates an object on the heap. In tight loops you prefer the primitive form to avoid the allocation cost.

Since Java ten, you can skip the type on a local variable declaration and let the compiler infer it from the right hand side. The keyword is var. This is purely a syntactic convenience. Java is still statically typed underneath, and the inferred type is fixed at compile time. The variable var name equals, in quotes, ganesh, becomes a string. The variable var scores equals new int array of ninety, eighty five, seventy eight, becomes an int array. The keyword var is only allowed on local variables, and only when there is an initializer on the right hand side. You cannot write var x with no initializer. You cannot write var y equals null, because null does not have an inferable type. And you cannot use var on fields of a class.

Use var when the type is obvious from the right hand side and adds nothing to readability. Spell the type out when the right hand side is a method call whose return type is non obvious. The compiler does not care. Future you, reading the file, will care.

Now, a core distinction in Java's grammar. An expression produces a value. The arithmetic one plus two is an expression. A method call like name dot length is an expression. The ternary operator, condition question mark a colon b, is an expression. A statement, on the other hand, performs an action and does not produce a value. A variable declaration like int x equals five is a statement. An assignment is a statement. An if block is a statement. A while loop is a statement.

This is the opposite of Scala, where if, while, and for are themselves expressions that return values. In Java they are statements, and they cannot appear on the right hand side of an assignment. The one place Java did add a real expression form for control flow is the modern switch expression, introduced in Java fourteen. A switch expression produces a value, so you can assign its result to a variable.

Java's operators look like C, Python, and JavaScript. The arithmetic operators are plus, minus, star for multiplication, slash for division, and percent for modulo. The most important quirk to know is that integer division truncates toward zero. Seven divided by two is three, not three point five. If you want floating point division, cast at least one side to double first.

The comparison operators are less than, less than or equal, greater than, greater than or equal, double equals for equality, and exclamation equals for inequality. The big Java gotcha lives here. For primitive types, double equals compares values. For reference types, double equals compares references. That means double equals on two string objects returns true only if both variables point to literally the same object on the heap. To compare two strings for content equality, you call the dot equals method. Burn this into your memory now. Double equals on objects compares identity. The dot equals method compares content. The only safe use of double equals on reference types is to check for null.

The logical operators are double ampersand for and, double pipe for or, and exclamation for not. Both double ampersand and double pipe short circuit, which means they stop evaluating as soon as the result is determined. The bitwise operators are single ampersand, single pipe, caret for exclusive or, tilde for bitwise not, double less than for left shift, and double greater than for arithmetic right shift. Java also has a third shift operator, triple greater than, which is an unsigned right shift. It is specific to Java and exists because Java does not have unsigned integer types.

Java's control flow statements are the C family with a few modern additions. The if, else if, and else statement is the classic conditional. The while loop and the do while loop are the pre and post test loops. The for loop comes in two forms. The classic three clause for, with initializer, condition, and update, gives you precise index control. The enhanced for loop, sometimes called the for each loop, lets you iterate over any iterable or array with the syntax for, paren, var element, colon collection, close paren. The switch statement and the switch expression handle multi way branching. And break and continue control loop flow.

The switch expression form, introduced in Java fourteen, is the modern way to use switch. You write switch on a value, then for each case use an arrow followed by the expression to return. You can group multiple labels with commas. You can use a default arm. The whole construct evaluates to a value you can assign. This is closer to Scala's pattern matching, and it is what you should reach for in new code.

A method is a named reusable block of code that lives inside a class. Every Java method declares its modifiers, its return type, its name, its parameter list in parentheses, and its body in braces. Methods marked static belong to the class itself rather than to an instance, and you call them on the class name. Methods without the static keyword belong to instances, and you call them on a variable holding an instance.

Java supports method overloading. Multiple methods can share the same name as long as their parameter lists differ. The compiler picks the right one at the call site based on the argument types. The keyword void marks a method that returns nothing. Unlike Scala's Unit, void is not a real type. It is a syntactic marker. You cannot declare a variable of type void.

Now, strings. The string class is the most used class in Java. Strings are immutable. Every operation that looks like it modifies a string actually returns a new string. The variable greeting holds the string hello. If you call greeting dot to upper case, you get back a new string HELLO in capital letters, and the original greeting variable still points to the lower case hello. Concatenation uses the plus operator. The String dot format method gives you printf style formatting. And since Java fifteen, the string class also has a dot formatted instance method that lets you write a format string followed by dot formatted, with the arguments in parentheses.

For multi line strings, Java fifteen added text blocks. A text block is a triple quoted string literal that preserves newlines and indentation rules. Triple quote, newline, content, triple quote. Text blocks are the cleanest way to embed JSON, structured query language, or HTML inside Java code. The compiler strips a common leading whitespace prefix from every line of the block, using the position of the closing triple quote as the baseline. This means you can indent the literal to match the surrounding code without that extra indentation appearing in the resulting string.

Java's comments follow the conventions you know from C and Scala. Two forward slashes start a single line comment that runs to the end of the line. Slash star starts a block comment that runs until the matching star slash. There is also a special form, slash star star, which begins a javadoc comment. Javadoc comments document public application programming interfaces, and tools like javadoc turn them into HTML reference documentation.

That is the on ramp. You now have Java twenty one installed. You can poke at it in the interactive shell. You can run a single file with jbang. And you can scaffold a real project with Maven. You also have the vocabulary in place. Values, primitive versus reference types, expressions versus statements, operators, var, control flow, methods, strings, and text blocks.

Notebook two starts object oriented Java in earnest. We will look at classes, inheritance, interfaces, abstract classes, and enums. We will look at the modern additions that change how you model data, especially records, sealed types, and pattern matching for switch. These are the shapes Spring will lean on later, so it is worth getting fluent with them now.
